content:
I'm sorry to hear that the solution I provided is not working as expected. Here's a revised solution that should work:

1. Remove the `background-color` property from the `.sticky-navbar` class in the CSS.
2. Add the `.transparent-navbar` class to the `navbar` element in the HTML:
```html
<nav class="navbar navbar-expand-lg navbar-light sticky-navbar sticky-top navbar-shadows transparent-navbar">
```
In this example, we're adding the `transparent-navbar` class to the `navbar` element.

1. Modify the JavaScript code to add and remove the `.transparent-navbar` class based on the scroll position:
```javascript
$(document).ready(function () {
  // Handle the navbar shrink effect on scroll
  $(window).scroll(function () {
    if ($(this).scrollTop() > 50) {
      $('.sticky-navbar').addClass('shrink');
      $('.sticky-navbar').removeClass('navbar-shadows');
      $('.transparent-navbar').removeClass('transparent-navbar');
    } else {
      $('.sticky-navbar').removeClass('shrink');
      $('.sticky-navbar').addClass('navbar-shadows');
      $('.navbar').addClass('transparent-navbar');
    }
  });
});
```
In this example, we're using the `scrollTop()` method to get the current scroll position of the window. When the user scrolls down the page, we remove the `.transparent-navbar` class from the `navbar` element to make the background color opaque, and when the user scrolls back to the top of the page, we add the `.transparent-navbar` class to make the background color transparent.

And that's it! Your navbar should now have a transparent background color only when not scrolling. If you still experience issues, please let me know and I'll try my best to help you.
